<section xml:id="C28.S11">
<title>Expansions in Series of Mathieu Functions</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C28.S11.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.s1">
Let <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.m1">f(z)</Math> be a <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.m2">2\pi</Math> -periodic function that is analytic in an open doubly-infinite strip <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.m3">S</Math> that contains the real axis, and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.m4">q</Math> be a normal value (§28.7).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.s2">
Then <Math equation-number="28.11.1" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S11.E1">f(z)=\alpha_{0}\mathrm{ce}_{0}\left(z,q\right)+\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\left(\alpha _{n}\mathrm{ce}_{n}\left(z,q\right)+\beta_{n}\mathrm{se}_{n}\left(z,q\right) \right),</Math> where <Math equation-number="28.11.2" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S11.E2">\alpha_{n}=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi}f(x)\mathrm{ce}_{n}\left(x,q\right) \mathrm{d}x,\beta_{n}=\frac{1}{\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi}f(x)\mathrm{se}_{n}\left(x,q\right) \mathrm{d}x</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.s3">
The series (28.11.1) converges absolutely and uniformly on any compact subset of the strip <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.m5">S</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.s4">
See Meixner and Schäfke (1954, §2.28), and for expansions in the case of the exceptional values of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S11.p1.m6">q</Math> seeMeixner et al. (1980, p. 33).
</sentence>

</para>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C28.S11.Px1">
<title>Examples</title>   
<para xml:id="C28.S11.Px1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C28.S11.Px1.p1.s1">
With the notation of §28.4,
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C28.S11.Px1.p1.s2">
<Math equation-number="28.11.3" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S11.E3">1=2\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}A_{0}^{2n}(q)\mathrm{ce}_{2n}\left(z,q\right),</Math> <Math equation-number="28.11.4" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S11.E4">\cos 2mz=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}A_{2m}^{2n}(q)\mathrm{ce}_{2n}\left(z,q\right), if m\neq 0,</Math> <Math equation-number="28.11.5" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S11.E5">\cos(2m+1)z=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}A_{2m+1}^{2n+1}(q)\mathrm{ce}_{2n+1}\left(z,q \right),</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.11.6" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S11.E6">\sin(2m+1)z=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}B_{2m+1}^{2n+1}(q)\mathrm{se}_{2n+1}\left(z,q \right),</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.11.7" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S11.E7">\sin(2m+2)z=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}B_{2m+2}^{2n+2}(q)\mathrm{se}_{2n+2}\left(z,q \right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
